review: i was really surprised by this novel. i was afraid that because the author was giving this out for free for stuff-your-kindle day, and so few people hi was really surprised by this novel. i was afraid that because the author was giving this out for free for stuff-your-kindle day, and so few people had read it, i wouldn't like it. but honestly, it was so good. this is genuinely one of the most well written fantasy romance novels ive read in such a long time. though i will say that fourth wing is not a good competitor. i loved getting to hear both perspectives in the novel; both the empress murderer and the daughter of the dead empress. while some of the s of the novel liked one perspective better than the other, i genuinely think both added to the story. i loved both main characters and their love interests, and i felt like they were such complex characters and i adored it. the first novel does a good job with world building and establishing the characters and their motivations. i also do love the side characters and the moral argument of "do we treat an entire group of people the way they treated us?". "'When the world is cruel to you, you're either cruel back or you lie down and die.' He clenched his jaw. review: the echo of old books was beautifully written, flitting between the past and present with not a hint of trouble. i absolutely loved the timeline of ththe echo of old books was beautifully written, flitting between the past and present with not a hint of trouble. i absolutely loved the timeline of the past (probably more than the current timelines), as i absolutely love the historical accuracy and the romance of the past. the romance wanted me to rip my hair out at times but i just loved the interactions between the male and female lead, especially since we got both perspectives. the fact that this was a book about books (the perspective changes between two different books and the main characters' perspectives) was absolutely lovely. i love that the female main character owns a bookstore and absolutely adores books (just like my dream!), and i love that she can sense the echoes of the past owners/readers emotions towards the books. im not sure historical romance is the only way to describe such a novel; it had mystery intertwined, romance and perhaps even a bit of contemporary fiction (argue you with me as much as you like contemporary fiction and romance are not the same). in the end, i really enjoyed the writing, the story, the characters, though i would have loved to see more of the interactions of the current timeline characters. i think this is a story about growing past trauma and past hurt to make new relationships, and relearning to trust that people won't be the same as the people who traumatized you. and i think that's something that's incredibly valuable."There is nothing quite so alive as a book that has been well loved" (5)."There's nothing more personal than a book, especially one that's become an important part of someone's life" (8)."'Books are feelings,' he replied simply. 'They exist to make us feel. To connect us to what's inside, sometimes to things we don't even know are there. It only makes sense that some of what we feel when we're reading...would rub off'" (8)."Like humans, books experienced their share of heartache—and like humans, they remembered" (9)."Without a reader, a book was a blank slate, an object with no breath or pulse of its own. But once a book became part of someone's world, it came to life, with a past and present—and, if properly cared for, a future" (10)."Where is human nature so weak as in a bookstore?" (15)."There was something enormously rewarding about taking something that had been neglected, even mistreated, and making it new again, deconstructing it with the greatest of care, then putting it back together again, its spine straightened, its scars removed, its tired beauty restored" (19)."'You have been the capital error of my life, the one regret for which there can be no absolution, no peace'" (23)."'Women aren't usually consulted on wars. author: Morrison, Toni

review: beloved. toni Morrison truly is a wonderful author, and i think i could read this a thousand times and i would find new things to discuss. the thing abeloved. toni Morrison truly is a wonderful author, and i think i could read this a thousand times and i would find new things to discuss. the thing about beloved is not that it's a so called enjoyable read. beloved is the most difficult novel i've ever read. the trauma that the characters go through because of the centuries of enslavement americans are often keen to push away and the way every single sentence and word has a hidden meaning. morrison wrote beloved with such intention that everything is so very complex. she questions identity, motherhood, memory, trauma - i could go on and on about the absract nouns she addresses in this one book. i don't think this a read for everyone; this needs to be read by people who genuinely care about reading this novel and trying to squeeze the precious meaning from every line. and certainly, it's difficult to read such a novel on your own, and that's why i think i couldn't have managed this without the emotional support of an entire class and ms Rosen who had read it many many times. there is a quiet horror to this novel, that creeps up on you when you're not looking and it's just overall a painful novel to read. but was it worth it in the end? yes. yes it was. and that's why it's so hard to write an essay that addresses the delicate topics in beloved and capture what needs to be captured. at the end of the day, i think i would say it's impossible to find every meaningful passage and analyze it. but i do think it's worth trying to find as many as you can....more

review: the water outlaws is based off a popular piece of Chinese martial arts literature. i don't actually know what the literature is, but the story remindethe water outlaws is based off a popular piece of Chinese martial arts literature. i don't actually know what the literature is, but the story reminded me of Robin Hood, like all stories of vigilantes always do. however, now, i'll associate vigilantes with lin chong, and her martial arts prowess (for the short period of time i remember this book). all of the women in the novel are so awe-inspiring, and i do love my strong women characters. i do have to say though, lu junyi is my absolute favorite character in the novel because of how she uses her wits to outsmart the enemy; risking EVERYTHING for a friend. the female relationships in this novel are excellent to say the least, and the sense of loyalty they all have for each other brings a metaphorical tear to my eye. the story started off slow, and I will not lie about the fact i nearly stopped reading it because i was bored. however, i kept reading it, and it was a heartwarming story. i would give it 3.5 stars because it was good but not that good, and i don't feel like it's worth of 4 stars (even though the cover is STUNNING) because it was just not a stand out novel. for my customary quotes:"Reality did not hew neatly to imagined archetypes" (131)."Nothing in this world was as it seemed. review: i don't know what i gave the first book but this one is definitely a 4.5. bloodmarked continues from where legendborn left off. i won't say where legei don't know what i gave the first book but this one is definitely a 4.5. bloodmarked continues from where legendborn left off. i won't say where legendborn left off because it is way too good to spoil. i would like to say that this book was somehow better than legendborn (which is impossible because legendborn was so good). maybe it's the hardcover speaking or the tension between two people (not telling you who!). the author does such a wonderful job of portraying grief and trauma. oftentimes, in magical settings, we forget about the intense trauma these young people are going through. fighting off monsters that could murder you is scary. facing situations that require you to be in constant flight or fight mode have a toll on the body, and bloodmarked doesn't shy away from this. ancestry is brought up again, especially living with the generational trauma passed down and how people deal with that. especially as a person of color. it also continues to address (A LOT) in this book how primarily white institutions try to keep people of color out of power. and how POC voices are lost because of the power white people wield in society, the idea of generational power emerging. the intent of white people in power to erase the horribly racist past of their ancestors is truly disgusting, and was another important subject addressed in this novel. i'm not sure if this  holds up to how amazing this book was, writing it so many days later, but it was genuinely such a powerful novel.here are my customary quotes."How must it feel to hold death in one hand and restoration in the other?" title: What You Are Looking For Is in the Library
author: Aoyama, Michiko
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: what you are looking for is in the library is somewhat a collection of short stories, yet i don't think that fully captures the entirety of the novel.what you are looking for is in the library is somewhat a collection of short stories, yet i don't think that fully captures the entirety of the novel. characters reappear in each novel, often influencing a side character in each short story. the entire idea is that different people come to the community library, all in search of something different. however, the librarian gives them more than they ask for, an additional book not related to their search and a token she's felted. the book manages to teach the different people different life lessons based on what they needed the most, and it's all achieved through them purposefully finding the significance in what they've received. the librarian has a bit of a supernatural air around her, but isn't a library always magical? what i enjoyed the most though is that while the people took inspiration from the books they received, they learn the lessons on their own. it makes the novel seem mundane, which has the strange beauty of every day life to it. i think everyone should read this because it was a calming read. pretty quotes"'In a world where you don't know what will happen next, I just do what I can right now'" (42)."'It's not always a bad thing to have a dream, with no plan for ever carrying it out'" (77)."'While I do believe that it was hard work for my mother to give birth to me, it also took me every ounce of my own strength to endure the extremely difficult process of being born'" (140)."'The majority may not accept something, but as long as there are some who do, the existence of that thing—whatever it may be—is protected'" (219). title: Let the Great World Spin
author: McCann, Colum*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: “The thing about love is that we come alive in bodies not our own” (175). let the great world spin is a novel that i never would have thought i liked.“The thing about love is that we come alive in bodies not our own” (175). let the great world spin is a novel that i never would have thought i liked. not in a million years. this is not the genre i usually read, nor a well known author (at least in our time) or a cover that screams for me to pick it up. however, i think this was a brilliantly written novel by Colum McCann. i have so many thoughts and so many ideas, but really, as i said in this class, the central idea of this novel is to let the great world spin. we're offered so many stories, from so many different people, all who are struggling through the monumental mess of grief. what does one do when confronted with grief? we're offered this answer throughout the novel. grief, somehow makes the world smaller. grief connects people through the most twisted pathways, yet the characters are able to find solace. these new connections, along with the tightrope walker (shoutout to filip petit), shows that the world keeps moving on no matter what has changed. grief and its impermanence is beautiful in a sense. how else can we find the courage to move on if grief was the sole thing that defined us for the rest of our lives? the answer is that we cannot. nothing is ever simple here, and nothing is every so simple in real life. McCann rewrites our categorization of people, changing the way we see everyone.“I sit there thinking about how much courage it takes to live an ordinary life” (56)....more

review: guys this book is so good so far im loving the stories shaherazad is tellingI had a lot of time to read this novel today, and it was gorgeous. 4.5 staguys this book is so good so far im loving the stories shaherazad is tellingI had a lot of time to read this novel today, and it was gorgeous. 4.5 stars. this is a retelling of the story 1001 Arabian nights, a staple of my childhood. shaherazad is what i imagine powerful queens to be like in the stories of old that prove that women played a role in society though they weren't afforded the same freedom as men. the stories shaherazad spins remind me of the books my mother read me when i was younger, full of adventures and lessons to be learned. the way she shapes the world with her tales emphasizes the point that stories have the power to change the world. im not sure how i felt about the open ended conclusion of the story, but there was a strange beauty in it. her story is not finished, and neither will the book give her a conclusion. what i thought was beautiful was the family bonds in the story. i feel like often, found family is frequent but the idea of a loyal family bound by blood doesn't exist. to shaherazad, her family means the world, and she goes to every length to protect them. the writing is so so so stunning, and i look forward to future novels by this author.“Men and women before you have been betrayed, and men and women after you will be betrayed. author: Mandel, Emily St. John*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: sea of tranquility was a PERFECT book club read. the plot weaves throughout time, sometimes forgetting that time is a barrier. however. i will say thasea of tranquility was a PERFECT book club read. the plot weaves throughout time, sometimes forgetting that time is a barrier. however. i will say that treating time as a social construct to be disregarded makes the comprehension of the story nonexistent, which makes it perfect to read in a group. i really loved the element of nature, whether it be the moon or the trees. i also appreciate how much we can analyze here due to Mandel's amazing writing. she is truly a brilliant author, as i cannot say this would be easy to write, especially since everything is interconnected, including her other books (station eleven + the glass hotel) . the amount of research taken into writing the book, as well as even being vulnerable enough to put some parallels to her own life in here is awe-inspiring. everything feels intentional and that's quite the great art to master in writing. every word lends a greater meaning to the general atmosphere of the moment occurring and i think the art of writing such a short book with so much meaning is a depiction of her true creativity. Mandel especially struck a chord with me with the inclusion of so much plague/illness, including a pandemic that im sure everyone can remembering with haunting clarity. thank you for enjoying sea of tranquility with me guys!pieces of elegant writing"Edwin is capable of action but prone to inertia" (5)."A life of solitude could be a very pleasant thing" (7)."Sometimes you don't know you're going to throw a grenade until you've already pulled the pin" (14)."If there's pleasure in action, there's peace in stillness" (23)."Fainting was darkness, but also sound: a murmuring and chirping like a chorus of birds, a blank void followed rapidly by an impression of being comfortably at home in bed — wishful thinking on the part of his subconscious, presumably — and then he woke into utter silence" (32)."For a woman alone in a park after nightfall, every neighborhood is a bad neighborhood" (52)."The things we see when we're young, sometimes they don't stay with us" (53)."Sometimes order can be relentless" (68)."In any given crowd, several people will inevitable be incurably sick, and several others will have recently lost someone they love to illness" (82)."'Look,' Olive said, 'the thing is, it's possible to be grateful for extraordinary circumstances and simultaneously long to be with the people you love'" (85)."There's a low-level, specific pain in having to accept that putting up with you requires a certain generosity of spirit in your loved ones" (116)." —Because of that ancient horror, to embarrassingly irrational to be articulated aloud: if you say the name of the thing you fear, might you attract that thing's attention?" (120)."'Perhaps we believe on some level that if the world were to end and be remade, if some unthinkable catastrophe were to occur, then perhaps we might be remade too, perhaps into better, more heroic, more honorable people'" (188)."'Because we might reasonably think of the end of the world,' Olive said, 'as a continuous and never-ending process'" (190)."'My personal belief is that we turn to postapocalyptic fiction bit because we're drawn to disaster, per se, but because we're drawn to what we imagine might come next. We long secretly for a world with less technology in it'" (191)."This is the strange lesson of living in a pandemic: life can be tranquil in the face of death" (195)....more

review: i was right for waiting so long to read this. the novel started off great. i really enjoyed the idea of seeing how "heroes" live 10 years later. the ai was right for waiting so long to read this. the novel started off great. i really enjoyed the idea of seeing how "heroes" live 10 years later. the alternating documents and chapters was really engaging, and this novel was definitely better than divergent. but, then, the main character turned out to be not a morally ambiguous person, but a kinda bad person. i feel like she didn't care enough about the people who saved the world with her except albie. she just kept going on and on about how annoying they are. they had valid concerns; why are you blowing a place up and killing people without telling us, why are you just disappearing when there's a VILLAIN on the lose trying to kill you. she just had no empathy for anyone and didn't care about anyone except herself. her relationships with people felt so one dimensional. the entire premise of her character is that she's wrapped in guilt and trauma of what she did. but it doesn't excuse the way she treats everyone else. i really wanted to see the trope of found family here, but really what i saw was a found family and then her being annoying. everyone around her was telling her she needed help but she absolutely refused and then hurt everyone around her. and the end was positively terrible. no joke. i won't spoil but i promise it sucks. i wish i could forget this book and im incredibly glad i got it for sale for 8 dollars in Maine. the other book i got from Maine for cheap (spinning silver) was definitely much better. i should have gotten uprooted (the other naomi novik book available on sale there). what a waste of a beautiful cover.quotes written down on my target receipt"The lost time had plagued her more than she would have expected it to - the idea that her body had no memory of is own, that she could not interrogate it for the answer" (245)."All the most powerful things she knew were also destructive unless diluted in some way" (392)....more

review: all of us villains is a novel about seven families in a small city competing every blood moon to win access to high magic. each family choses a champiall of us villains is a novel about seven families in a small city competing every blood moon to win access to high magic. each family choses a champion, and they're all forced to kill each other within 3 months (with no access to the outside world), with spell rings. I was scared to purchase this novel, if only because the s seem so conflicted and the blurb doesn't effectively capture what actually happens in the novel. the one star s don't have any real issue with the book except that everyone doesn't always act like a villain. however, there's a lot of moral ambiguity through the novel which really made it for me. alliances are created and destroyed, and enemies and friends seem no different. the relationships in the novel are so complex, and the personalities created so beautifully, that we don't know which person to root for. I don't agree with the idea that this book is not worth reading these people don't act villainous. i think it's unfair to expect characters to be truly villainous without any regret. that would make this quite the boring book. the inner conflict is what makes these people real, proving that they have their humanity. i think being villainous is the moral ambiguity of the so called villain. i also think that these families are villainous. the entire premise of the novel is that these families kill each other for power. i feel like that's quite villainous."He was a dagger in the darkness, quiet blood spilled on nightclothes, a scream that died in your throat" (159)....more

title: Half of a Yellow Sun
author: Adichie, Chimamanda Ngozi
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: half of a yellow sun was one of the most educational and deeply touching novels i've ever read. the novel starts off somewhat happy, exploring the inthalf of a yellow sun was one of the most educational and deeply touching novels i've ever read. the novel starts off somewhat happy, exploring the intricacies of the relationships between people and the people themselves. the conversations were educational; the political views heard through the intellectual discussions held in the novel introduced me to Nigeria pre-civil war without giving me long blocks of information i didn't understand. every perspective the novel has is so engaging, and i never felt bored reading a single chapter. the characters are so three dimensional, and well thought as well as nuanced in the way real people are (though i may say that ugwu was the heart as adhichie herself says). no relationship is singularly perfect, no person perfect. and that's what lends to the humanity that crushes a reader in this novel. the painstaking detail used to describe everything, including the most violent parts are what make it necessary to read. half a yellow sun should be read by everyone.the civil war in Nigeria was bloody and terrible as all wars are, however, the igbo genocide makes this infinite times worse. the igbo people were murdered brutally and not a single nation cared. i don't think how i can describe the feeling of reading about exactly how these people were killed, and i can't imagine how anyone could voice their experience. but someone was brave enough to do so, and here we have a novel based on that. however, i think that there needs to more books on this. more information offered to the general public. as adichie herself says in her famous ted talk "the danger of a single story", there cannot be a single narrative for such a horrific time in history. adichie's others novel(s?) address the Nigerian civil war, the only one i can think of on the spot Purple Hibiscus. but there needs to be more people telling the story of the history that western media doesn't want to tell. a primary aspect of the novel was the people who wrote down what happened, and it addressed how western journalists dramatized incidents and changed them to match the narrative they believed to be true. the blatant racism and superiority these journalists felt disgusted me; we still see that in western media today. the media we consume here in america chooses to ignore the positive aspects of these countries, or even the perspectives of people living there. they propose a single narrative, and it's extremely dangerous because this is what the masses of america read. they form opinions and biases and develop prejudice because of the biased journalism. so i can't imagine what Americans thought of the Nigerian civil war, or if they even knew about it. the author also addresses the consequences of colonialism, the one standing out the most to me the idea of separating people of a country. the British had the mindset of dividing and conquering, so they excarberated and created tensions between groups they governed. in the end, this did end up causing the Nigerian civil war. but did it? did the British create this idea of being separate or did these groups already exist separately? would uniting prove the British idea that all these people are the same? that all people of a certain race are a same? these ideas are called into question throughout the novel, and i think it was extremely powerful.i have so many other thoughts, but i think I'll end it here so people can make their own conclusions after reading. this book is necessary for people to read because of its transparency. the transparency is triggering, but this narrative should not be a forgotten one.sentences that provoked thought and emotion"'Education is a priority! How can we resist exploitation if we don't have the tools to understand exploitation?'" (13)."'I am Nigerian because a white man created Nigeria and gave me that identity. I am black because the white man constructed black to be as different as possible from his white. But I was Igbo before the white man came'" (25)."It was as if the scent could at least for a while, stifle her questions and make her a little more like him, a little more certain, a little less questioning" (33)."Olanna wished they would; it was such a simple thing to do, to acknowledge the humanity of the people who served them" (37)."She was used to this, being grabbed by men who walked around in a cloud of cologne-drenched entitlement, with the presumption that, because they were powerful and found her beautiful, they belonged together" (41)."She felt a sense that things were in order, the way they were meant to be, and that even if they tumbled down once in a while, in the end they would come back together again" (49)."He looked as if it were he who was receiving a gift; he had that expression of people who marveled at education with the calm certainty that it would never be theirs" (50). "It came with never having had much, she knew, the inability to let go of things, even things that were useless" (59)."They were too happy, precariously so, and she wanted to guard that bond; she feared that marriage would flatten it to a prosaic partnership" (65)."'The real tragedy of our postcolonial world is not that the majority of people had no say or not they wanted this new world; rather, it is that the majority have not been given the tools to negotiate this new world'" (129)."This was love; a string of coincidences that gathered significance and became miracles" (135)."Is love this misguided need to have you beside me most of the time? Is love this safety I feel in our silence? Is it this belonging, this completeness?'" (189)."'Of course, we all hate somebody, but it's about control. Civilization teaches you control'" (194)."If only he could reach out and tug at her lips to remove the sad smile on her face. If only it took that little." (251). "She wanted to ask them why they were all strangers who shared the same last name" (273)."Olanna gently placed a pillow beneath her head and sat thinking about how a single act could reverberate over time and space and leave stains that could never be washed out"' (306)."Unbroken happiness is a bore; it should have ups and downs" (322)."He had read somewhere that, for true writers, nothing was more important than their art, not even love" (324)."'The world has to know the truth of what is happening, because they simply cannot remain silent while we die" (383)."'I was a new person because I no longer had family to remind me of what I had been'" (401)."He was not living his life; life was living him" (457)."...the rule of Western journalism: One hundred dead black people equal one dead white person" (462)."Grief was the celebration of love, those who could feel real grief were luck to have loved" (538)....more

review: sword catcher by cassandra clare did not disappoint cassandra clare's long legacy of writing incredible fantasy. the cover is eye catching with the resword catcher by cassandra clare did not disappoint cassandra clare's long legacy of writing incredible fantasy. the cover is eye catching with the red and gold, and the design around the edges, and like her other novels, is long at a whopping 604 pages (no wonder the author of game of thrones said it was everything he looks for in fantasy!). the story is about an orphan who bears a striking resemblance to the crown prince of castellane, so he is chosen to become the sword catcher for the prince. in essence, this means what the name literally says; he catches swords for the prince by being the prince in dangerous situations. the other perspective we're offered is lin caster, one of the ashkar, which is the only group in the world who still has magic. the ashkar are clearly inspired by the jewish people, their language inspired by hebrew, and cassandra clare herself writing that she hopes her non-Jewish readers can gain some understanding into the complexity of being jewish in a society that isn't exactly friendly to them. I am STUNNED because i have not a clue how she manages to build such elaborate worlds. everything is so well thought out, the characters complex, the plot complex, EVERYTHING is so intricate. i just love the romance in here, and that it could exist without the romance and still be a wonderful book. i find myself lately shying away from romance, and this book delivered the high quality fantasy i needed while giving me the tidbits of romance i love looking for. there are a lot of complaints about the information dump but honestly, i love learning about the magical world. isn't one of the best parts of fantasy the magic and the transport to a different universe? why would i choose a novel that gave me less details and less back pain from carrying it around?please read this my fellow fantasy lovers. once you're done reading the 2000 other novels i've recommended. I didn't get the chance to track many quotes, but the couple i got don't even begin to adequately show how beautiful certain parts of this novel are written."It was a beauty that seemed made of bright pieces, like glittering tesserae that came together to form something almost frighteningly magnificent: a great archway or spired castle" (386)."In the small hours of the night, between the watches of sickness, between fever and recovery, perhaps everyone was a little bit the same" (213)....more
